Title: 
 Risk Premia and Variance Bounds.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 1913-49
Issue: 5
Volume: 52
Year: 1997
Month:  December 
Abstract:

 If a pricing kernel assigns a premium to a risk variable that differs
 from the one assigned by the minimum-variance admissible kernel, then the
 pricing kernel must exhibit more variability than the minimum-variance
 kernel. Based on this intuition, the authors derive a variance bound that
 is more stringent than that of Lars Peter Hansen and Ravi Jagannathan
 (1991). When the authors apply their bound to the kernel of a
 representative consumer with power utility, they find that the consumption
 risk premium increases the severity of the 'equity-premium puzzle' of
 Rajnish Mehra and Edward C. Prescott (1985).


