  Fama, Eugene F
Author-Name:  French, Kenneth R
Title: 
 The CAPM Is Wanted, Dead or Alive.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 1947-58
Issue: 5
Volume: 51
Year: 1996
Month:  December 
Abstract:

 Kothari, Shanken, and Sloan (1995) claim that betas from annual returns
 produce a stronger positive relation between beta and average return than
 betas from monthly returns. They also contend that the relation between
 average return and book-to-market equity (BE/ME) is seriously exaggerated
 by survivor bias. We argue that survivor bias does not explain the
 relation between BE/ME and average return. We also show that annual and
 monthly betas produce the same inferences about the beta premium. Our main
 point on the beta premium is, however, more basic. It cannot save the
 Capital asset pricing model (CAPM), given the evidence that beta alone
 cannot explain expected return.


