Title: 
 Transactions Costs and Capital Structure Choice: Evidence from Financially Distressed Firms.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 161-96
Issue: 1
Volume: 52
Year: 1997
Month:  March 
Abstract:

 This study provides evidence that transaction costs discourage debt
 reductions by financially distressed firms when they restructure their
 debt out of court. As a result, these firms remain highly leveraged and
 one-in-three subsequently experience financial distress. Transactions
 costs are significantly smaller, hence leverage falls by more and there is
 less recurrence of financial distress when firms recontract in Chapter 11.
 Chapter 11 therefore gives financially distressed firms more flexibility
 to choose optimal capital structures.


