Title: 
 Tick Size, Share Prices, and Stock Splits.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 655-81
Issue: 2
Volume: 52
Year: 1997
Month:  June 
Abstract:

 Minimum price variation rules help explain why stock prices vary
 substantially across countries and other curiosities of share prices.
 Companies tend to split their stock so that the institutionally mandated
 minimum tick size is optimal relative to the stock price. A large relative
 tick size provides an incentive for dealers to make markets and for
 investors to provide liquidity by placing limit orders, despite its
 placing a high floor on the quoted bid-ask spread. A simple model suggests
 that idiosyncratic risk, firm size, and visibility of the firm affect the
 optimal relative tick size and thus the share price.


