Title: 
 Analyst Following of Initial Public Offerings.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 507-29
Issue: 2
Volume: 52
Year: 1997
Month:  June 
Abstract:

 The authors examine data on analyst following for a sample of initial
 public offerings completed between 1975 and 1987 to see how they related
 to three well-documented initial public offering (IPO) anomalies. They
 find that higher underpricing leads to increased analyst following.
 Analysts are overoptimistic about the earnings potential and long-term
 growth prospects of recent IPOs. More firms complete IPOs when analysts
 are particularly optimistic about the growth prospects of recent IPOs. In
 the long run, IPOs have better stock performance when analysts ascribe low
 growth potential rather than high growth potential. These results suggest
 that the anomalies may be partially driven by overoptimism.


