Title: 
 Institutions and Individuals at the Turn-of-the-Year.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 1543-62
Issue: 4
Volume: 52
Year: 1997
Month:  September 
Abstract:

 This article evaluates the tax-loss-selling hypothesis against the
 window-dressing hypothesis as explanations for turn-of-the-year anomalies.
 The authors examine differences between securities dominated by individual
 investors versus those dominated by institutional investors and find that
 the effect is more pervasive in the former. Controlling for
 capitalization, they find that, in early January (late December), stocks
 with greater individual investor interest outperform (underperform) stocks
 with greater institutional investor interest. These results hold for both
 stocks that previously appreciated in value and stocks that previously
 depreciated in value. The results are more consistent with the
 tax-loss-selling hypothesis as an explanation for the turn-of-the-year
 effect.


