 on size and book-to-market. They find that the risk premium on size that
 was estimated by Eugene F. Fama and Kenneth R. French (1992) completely
 disappears when the 1 percent most extreme observations are trimmed each
 month. The authors also show that the negative average of the monthly size
 coefficients reported by Fama and French can be entirely explained by the
 sixteen months with the most extreme coefficients. They argue that further
 investigation of these results could lead to an understanding of the
 economic forces underlying the size effect, and may also yield important
 insights into how firms grow.


