Volume: 51
Year: 1996
Month:  March 
Abstract:

 Capital requirements linked solely to credit risk are shown to increase
 equilibrium credit rationing and lower aggregate lending. The model
 predicts that the bank's decision to lend will cause an abnormal run-up in
 the borrower's stock price and that this reaction will be greater the more
 capital-constrained the bank. The author provides empirical support for
 this prediction. The model explains the recent inability of the Federal
 Reserve to stimulate bank lending by increasing the money supply. He shows
 that increasing the money supply can either raise or lower lending when
 capital requirements are linked only to credit risk.


