Abstract:

 This investigation of the cross-section of mutual fund equity holdings
 for the years 1991 and 1992 shows that mutual funds have a significant
 preference towards stocks with high visibility and low transaction costs,
 and are averse to stocks with low idiosyncratic volatility. These findings
 are relevant to theories concerning investor recognition, a potential
 agency problem in mutual funds, tests of trend-following and herd behavior
 by mutual funds, and corporate finance.


