Abstract:

 American corporations earn a significant share of their profits from
 foreign sources, out of which they appear to pay dividends at rates that
 are three times higher than their payout rates from domestic profits. Why
 firms do so is unclear, although this behavior is consistent with the use
 of dividends to signal profitability. This payout behavior implies that a
 significant part of the U.S. tax revenue generated by the foreign profits
