 Trading systems differ in their degree of transparency, here defined as
 the extent to which marketmakers can observe the size and direction of the
 current order flow. The authors investigate whether greater transparency
 enhances market liquidity by reducing the opportunities for taking
 advantage of uninformed participants. They compare the price formation
 process in several stylized trading systems with different degrees of
