Abstract:

 The author documents a dramatic increase in the importance of two types
 of variation in Treasury bill yields beginning in the early 1980s. The
 first is idiosyncratic variation in individual short-maturity (less than
 three months) bill yields. The second is a common component in Treasury
 bill yields that is not shared by yields on other instruments, such as
 short-maturity privately issued instruments or longer-maturity Treasury
 notes and bonds. Some evidence suggests the first type reflects increased
 market segmentation. These results have important implications for the
 calibration and testing of no-arbitrage term structure models and
 interpreting tests of the expectations hypothesis.


