Title: 
 Equilibrium Analysis of Portfolio Insurance.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 1379-1403
Issue: 4
Volume: 51
Year: 1996
Month:  September 
Abstract:

 A martingale approach is used to characterize general equilibrium in the
 presence of portfolio insurance. Insurers sell to noninsurers in bad
 states and general equilibrium requires that the risk premium rises to
 induce noninsurers to increase their holdings. The authors show that
 portfolio insurance increases price volatility, causes mean reversion in
 asset returns, raises the Sharpe ratio and volatility in bad states, and
 causes volatility to be correlated with volume. They also explain why
 out-of-the-money S&P 500 put options trade at a higher volatility than do
 in-the-money puts.


