  Wagster, John D
Title: 
 Impact of the 1988 Basle Accord on International Banks.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 1321-46
Issue: 4
Volume: 51
Year: 1996
Month:  September 
Abstract:

 The ostensible purpose of the Basle Accord was to standardize
 bank-capital regulations among the twelve leading industrial countries.
 Its ulterior goal was to 'level the playing field' by eliminating a
 funding-cost advantage of Japanese banks that had allowed them to capture
 more than one-third of international lending. The wealth gain for Japanese
 bank shareholders was 31.63 percent. Wealth effects for shareholders of
 non-Japanese banks were not significant. These results suggest that the
 Baste Accord did not eliminate the pricing advantage of Japanese banks,
 challenging the non-Japanese regulators' contention that the regulation
 would help level the playing field.


