Title: 
 The Capital Budgeting Process: Incentives and Information.

Journal: Journal of Finance
Pages: 1139-74
Issue: 4
Volume: 51
Year: 1996
Month:  September 
Abstract:

 The authors study the capital allocation process within firms. Observed
 budgeting processes are explained as a response to decentralized
 information and incentive problems. It is shown that these imperfections
 can result in underinvestment when capital productivity is high and
 overinvestment when it is low. The authors also investigate how the
 budgeting process may be expected to vary with firm or division
 characteristics, such as investment opportunities and the technology for
 information transfer.


